x4freetext: Angle-integrated energy spectra
A 215 mug/cm2 self-supporting foil of nat-Si of 18 mm
diameter. The target holder was set at a potential of
+18-kv to suppress secondary electron emission.
Light charged particlts emitted at
backward angles were detected and identified in seven
triple-Si E-delta-E telescopes. The Si-detectors with
thicknesses of 85, 706, and 706-mum, respectively.
At forward angles, light charged
particles were detected in eight E-delta-E telescopes.
The telescopes were used for the first
experiment with the proton beams at forward angles.
The Si delta-E element was 40 mum thick and of 20 mm
active diameter.  This was followed by a 33 mm-thick
Cs(I) crystal of 15 mm diameter.
Neutrons emitted in coincidence with charged
particles were detected in up to 81 Demon counters.
Each counter, consisting of an active volume of 16 cm
diameter by 20 cm depth, is filled with Ne213
liquid scintillator.  These detectors were mounted
outside the scattering chamber and were arranged in a
4-pi geometry

x4freetext: The beams were chopped to produce a macro-time
structure of one beam pulse every 500 nanoseconds and
thus allow the detection of very long time-of-flight
events (especially neutrons).
Electron emission from this faraday cup was
suppressed by a guard electrode.
The dead time of acquisition data system was very
severely controlled and kept below 10% even though
related corrections were applied to the data.
From the authors.
